         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Silk Farm. ¶ Plenty Road. ¶ Collingwood. ¶ Thursday. July 24. 1879 ¶ My dear Baron:—...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">79.07.24</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Ann Timbrell</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Miscellaneous reports 7.7, Victoria, Miscellaneous 1861-1916 (MR/412), f. 345.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M forwarded this letter, together with the samples associated with it, to J. Hooker; see M to J. Hooker, 27 July 1879 (in this edition as <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>79-07-27a).</p>
               </note>Silk Farm.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Plenty Road.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Collingwood.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Melbourne.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Thursday. July 24. 1879</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Baron:—</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am sincerely obliged to you for your kindness; and am delighted to hear of your accession to the title of K.C.M.G. but I am afraid that you have over-estimated my small silk samples from the Osage Orange.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In the second edition of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Select extra-tropical plants</seg> (B81.13.10), p. 185, M noted under <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Maclura aurantiaca</seg>: 'Mrs Timbrell, at the surmise of the author, has shown that the foliage is as good a food for silkworms as that of the white mulberry, and the silk produced is no way inferior to ordinary silk.'</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I now enclose another curiosity. Some months ago, I noticed a paragraph in one of the newspapers, about a M. Brunet having succeeded in obtaining "<seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Silk from the bark of a mulberry tree</hi>
               </seg>": so, last night, I tried an experiment, with what result, you can now judge from the accompanying paper.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">A small piece of paper (about 9 x 11 cm.) is glued to the front of the folio. Two samples of fibre, one off-white, the other pinkish-purple, are attached by thread on one side of the paper, and below them Timbrell has written: 'Respectfully presented as a novelty in sericultural science to Baron Ferd. von Muëller. K.C.M.G. &amp;c &amp;c'</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Below the off-white sample she has written: 'natural: as extracted from mulberry bark' and below the purple one: 'dyed: with magenta'.</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Opposite these she has written: 'Mrs Timbrell's <seg style="">
                        <hi rend="underline">first</hi>
                     </seg> attempt at procuring a substitute for Silk, from <seg style="">
                        <hi rend="underline">the fibre of mulberry bark</hi>
                     </seg>. The experiment was made on the night of Wednesday, July 23. 1879, at her Silk Farm, Plenty Road, Collingwood near Melbourne. Probably, the next operation may be an improvement on the above result.'</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It is only interesting as a novelty in Sericultural Science; and, please to remember, it is only my first effort.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am going to try again: and, will send you some Silkworm eggs very soon.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Allowe me to remain</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Yours sincerely</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ann Timbrell<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The signature is in a much larger and freer hand than the text of the letter and the notes, in which the writing is small and almost Copperplate and may be that of an amanuensis.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>[…]<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">illegible</seg> — Obscured by binding.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
         </div>
      </body>
